{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":83696,"duration_api_ms":83648,"num_turns":4,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"f4f7b1cd-8c25-47b6-a88b-e49dc83a9a5e","total_cost_usd":0.3287984,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":24789,"cache_read_input_tokens":111336,"output_tokens":2531,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":24789,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":5,"outputTokens":2531,"cacheReadInputTokens":111336,"cacheCreationInputTokens":24789,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.27389925,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":32,"outputTokens":3098,"cacheReadInputTokens":75159,"cacheCreationInputTokens":25489,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.054899149999999994,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Independently verified all five amendments against source code. Four address real defects with clear fixes. The TransportFailure classification for unconfirmed teardowns (fr-21-093a1416) is intentional and defensible — the proposed new FailureClass adds cross-cutting complexity for marginal semantic benefit.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-21-7297fd7b","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed identical pattern-matching blocks at lines 1273-1284 and 1325-1336. Both check the same error variants and string patterns for timeout detection. Extracting into a helper fn is a textbook DRY improvement — if the heuristic changes (new error variant, different string match), a single-site update prevents drift between the two paths. Minimal risk, clear maintenance benefit."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-093a1416","decision":"reject","rationale":"The code comment at lines 1079-1083 explicitly documents the design intent: when the kill is unconfirmed, the process may still be alive, which is genuinely a transport/infrastructure problem rather than a simple timeout. Giving TransportFailure 5 retries vs Timeout's 3 is defensible — an unconfirmed kill warrants more retry headroom because the underlying issue (stuck process) may be transient. Adding FailureClass::UnconfirmedTimeout would ripple through retry_policy, journal serialization/deserialization, derive_resume_state, and test fixtures — substantial cross-cutting changes for a distinction that the current two-class model already handles adequately. The amendment identifies a real asymmetry but the proposed fix's cost outweighs its benefit."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-0153f5fb","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed at lines 1557-1563: spawn_background_reap calls force_kill() then wait().await with no timeout. On Linux, a process in uninterruptible I/O (D-state) will never exit from the kernel's perspective, causing the tokio task to block indefinitely and the Arc<ManagedChild> to leak permanently. This is not theoretical — D-state processes are common with NFS mounts, disk I/O errors, and FUSE filesystems. A bounded timeout (e.g., 30s) with a warning log on expiry is a straightforward, low-risk fix that prevents unbounded resource accumulation."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-eeb662d0","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified the bug chain: (1) fail_run() at line 5133-5138 swallows write_run_snapshot() errors and proceeds to journal run_failed; (2) resume_run_with_retry_internal() at line 1147-1158 checks snapshot.status FIRST and rejects Running with an error; (3) derive_resume_state() at line 1197 is called AFTER the status gate, so it's never reached. The code comment claims 'the journal is authoritative for derive_resume_state' but the snapshot status guard prevents derive_resume_state from ever being invoked. Result: a failed run with a stale Running snapshot is permanently unrecoverable — neither resume nor start will work. This is a real state-machine bug. Either the snapshot write must remain a hard failure, or the resume path must consult the journal before rejecting based on snapshot status."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-451f4174","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed: Command::new at line 985 spawns without process group isolation (no pre_exec/setsid), and send_signal at line 355 targets a single PID via kill(Pid::from_raw(pid), signal). Any child processes spawned by the backend CLI inherit the parent's process group and survive SIGKILL of the parent PID. These orphans can hold ports, lock files, or other resources and overlap with the next retry — a concrete correctness issue, not theoretical. Spawning into a dedicated process group (pre_exec setsid + kill(-pgid)) is the standard Unix fix for this class of problem and is well-understood."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"a54478d1-1a65-4813-ac60-ea529fc87718"}
